a href=\"http://www.c-thru-music.com/cgi/?page=prod_axis-64\" target=\"_blank\">AXis-64</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://lividinstruments.com/hardware_ohm.php\">Livid OHM</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.doepfer.de/ctm.htm\">Doepfer CTM</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://monome.org/series/\">Monome</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.global.yamaha.com/tenori-on\">Yamaha Tenori-On</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.zendrum.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Zendrum</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nModular Devices\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.doepfer.de/\">Doepfer</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://analoguehaven.com/\">Analogue Haven</a> is the exclusive North American reseller for Doepfer.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://synthesizers.com\" target=\"_blank\">Synthesizers.com</a> makes very similar devices to the Doepfer system, at a comparable price.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTheremins\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.thereminworld.com\" target=\"_blank\">Theremin World</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Audio Hardware',0,'','inherit','open','open','','90-revision-6','','','2008-08-25 15:57:30','2008-08-25 22:57:30','',90,'http://sounding.com/blog/?p=144',0,'revision','',0),(1134,2,'2019-08-20 16:20:26','2019-08-20 23:20:26','<h2>Non-DRM Distributors (digital and otherwise)</h2>\n<ul>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://www.boomkat.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Bookmat</a> is not only the home of the dubby Modern Love dance label, but also houses a huge selection of experimental / electronic label releases, physical and digital alike.</li>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://www.emusic.com/\">eMusic</a></li>\n 	<li><a href=\"http://downtownmusicgallery.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Downtown Music Gallery</a> in NYC now has a decent web presence and a way to order securely by email, and is probably one of the best alternative record stores I\'ve ever visited (multiple times!).</li>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://www.bleep.com\">Bleep</a> - for all intents and purposes, Bleep picked up where EFA left off, distributing not only Warp artists but a great many other European labels; in fact WarpMart has now merged into Bleep.</li>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://www.kompakt-net.com/\">Kompakt</a> is not only a great label with many sublabels, they also do a lot of European distribution as well, and is a great place for getting vinyl.</li>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://www.forcedexposure.com/\">Forced Exposure</a> is my go-to for experimental releases on vinyl, though they carry CDs as well. No digital distribution, but they do carry Buddha Machines!</li>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://hardwax.com/\">Hard Wax</a></li>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://www.juno.co.uk\">Juno</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Sound (and other) Art</h2>\n<ul>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://www.ubu.com\">UbuWeb</a> features free downloads of many well known fringe artists, including both sound and video.</li>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://www.soundtransit.nl/\">SoundTransit</a> is a collaborative, online community dedicated to field recording and phonography.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Free Samples and Loops</h2>\n<ul>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://freesound.iua.upf.edu/\">The Freesound Project</a> aims to create a huge collaborative database of audio snippets, samples, recordings, bleeps, etc. released under the Creative Commons Sampling Plus License.</li>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://www.soundsnap.com/\">Soundsnap</a> is another free sound sample and loop library.</li>\n 	<li> <a href=\"http://wiki.laptop.org/go/Sound_samples\">OLPC</a> (One Laptop Per Child) features \"Over 10GB of FREE Samples – for The Children of the World\"</li>\n</ul>','Get Some',0,'','inherit','closed','closed','','91-revision-v1','','','2019-08-20 16:20:26','2019-08-20 23:20:26','',91,'https://sounding.com/blog/2019/08/20/91-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(264,2,'2009-02-12 14:03:40','2009-02-12 21:03:40','<h2>Non-DRM Distributors (digital and otherwise)</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.boomkat.com\" target=\"_blank\">Bookmat</a> is not only the home of the dubby Modern Love dance label, but also houses a huge selection of experimental / electronic label releases, physical and digital alike.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.emusic.com/\">eMusic\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.bleep.com\">Bleep</a> - for all intents and purposes, Bleep picked up where EFA left off, distributing not only Warp artists but a great many other European labels; in fact WarpMart has now merged into Bleep.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.kompakt-net.com/\">Kompakt</a> is not only a great label with many sublabels, they also do a lot of European distribution as well, and is a great place for getting vinyl.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.forcedexposure.com/\">Forced Exposure</a> is my go-to for experimental releases on vinyl, though they carry CDs as well. No digital distribution, but they do carry Buddha Machines!</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://hardwax.com/\">Hard Wax</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.juno.co.uk\">Juno</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Sound (and other) Art</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.ubu.com\">UbuWeb</a> features free downloads of many well known fringe artists, including both sound and video.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.soundtransit.nl/\">SoundTransit</a> is a collaborative, online community dedicated to field recording and phonography.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Free Samples and Loops</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://freesound.iua.upf.edu/\">The Freesound Project</a> aims to create a huge collaborative database of audio snippets, samples, recordings, bleeps, etc. released under the Creative Commons Sampling Plus License.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.soundsnap.com/\">Soundsnap</a> is another free sound sample and loop library.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://wiki.laptop.org/go/Sound_samples\">OLPC</a> (One Laptop Per Child) features \"Over 10GB of FREE Samples – for The Children of the World\"</li>\r\n</ul>','Get Some',0,'','inherit','open','open','','91-revision-3','','','2009-02-12 14:03:40','2009-02-12 21:03:40','',91,'http://sounding.com/blog/?p=264',0,'revision','',0),(146,2,'2008-07-06 16:49:57','2008-07-06 23:49:57','<h2>Non-DRM Distributors (digital and otherwise)</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://audiolunchbox.com\">Audio Lunchbox</a> - one of my favorite sites for finding independent music, many labels will put just a few releases here for archival purposes or simply to have something on the site. it\'s great for purchasing good music not only because you can preview everything, but they have an awesome subscription deal: $10 a month gets you 40 \'credits\', and typically a credit is equivalent to a dollar, which is the cost per track. So for 10 bucks you get the equivalent buying power of 40!</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.emusic.com/\">eMusic</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.bleep.com\">Bleep</a> - for all intents and purposes, Bleep picked up where EFA left off, distributing not only Warp artists but a great many other European labels.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.kompakt-net.com/\">Kompakt</a> is not only a great label with many sublabels, they also do a lot of European distribution as well, and is a great place for getting vinyl.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.forcedexposure.com/\">Forced Exposure</a> is my go-to for experimental releases on vinyl, though they carry CDs as well. No digital distribution.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://hardwax.com/\">Hard Wax</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.juno.co.uk\">Juno</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Sound (and other) Art</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.ubu.com\">UbuWeb</a> features free downloads of many well known fringe artists, including both sound and video.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.soundtransit.nl/\">SoundTransit</a> is a collaborative, online community dedicated to field recording and phonography.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Free Samples and Loops</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://freesound.iua.upf.edu/\">The Freesound Project</a> aims to create a huge collaborative database of audio snippets, samples, recordings, bleeps, etc. released under the Creative Commons Sampling Plus License.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.soundsnap.com/\">Soundsnap</a> is another free sound sample and loop library.</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://wiki.laptop.org/go/Sound_samples\">OLPC</a> (One Laptop Per Child) features \"Over 10GB of FREE Samples – for The Children of the World\"</li>\r\n</ul>','Get Some',0,'','inherit','open','open','','91-revision','','','2008-07-06 16:49:57','2008-07-06 23:49:57','',91,'http://sounding.com/blog/?p=146',0,'revision','',0),(260,2,'2008-09-18 13:33:50','2008-09-18 20:33:50','DIY Electronics\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.anti-theory.com/soundart/circuitbend/\" target=\"_blank\">Circuit-Bending Howto</a> at Anti-Theory.com</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.getlofi.com/\" target=\"_blank\">GetLoFi</a> Circuit Bending Synth DIY: \"Circuit Bending tips and resources for Beginners and Pros alike.\"</li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.musicfromouterspace.com/analogsynth.php?page=ANALOG\">Music from Outer Space</a> has analog synth examples and resources.</li>\r\n	<li>Georgia Tech has lectures and coursework online for <a href=\"http://users.ece.gatech.edu/%7Elanterma\"></a>Aaron Lanterman\'s <a href=\"http://users.ece.gatech.edu/~lanterma/ems/\" target=\"_blank\">Electronics for Music Synthesis</a> class.</li>\r\n	<li>MIT\'s online <a href=\"http://ocw.mit.edu/OcwWeb/Electrical-Engineering-and-Computer-Science/6-002Spring-2007/CourseHome/index.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Circuits and Electronics</a> course.<a href=\"http://users.ece.gatech.edu/~lanterma/ece4803/\" target=\"_blank\"></a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nPCB modules\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.arduino.cc/\" target=\"_blank\">Arduino</a> \"is an open-source electronics prototyping platform\" whereby users can insert software code onto an outboard chipset to make custom hardware effects.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\"Pad\" (MIDI) controllers\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.c-thru-music.com/cgi/?page=prod_axis-64\" target=\"_blank\">AXis-64</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://lividinstruments.com/hardware_ohm.php\">Livid OHM</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.doepfer.de/ctm.htm\">Doepfer CTM</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://monome.org/series/\">Monome</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.global.yamaha.com/tenori-on\">Yamaha Tenori-On</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.zendrum.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Zendrum</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nModular Devices\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://www.doepfer.de/\">Doepfer</a></li>\r\n	<li> <a href=\"http://analoguehaven.com/\">Analogue Haven</a> is the exclusive North American reseller for Doepfer.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://synthesizers.com\" target=\"_blank\">Synthesizers.com</a> makes very similar devices to the Doepfer system, at a comparable price.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTheremins\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.thereminworld.com\" target=\"_blank\">Theremin World</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Audio Hardware',0,'','inherit','open','open','','90-revision-8','','','2008-09-18 13:33:50','2008-09-18 20:33:50','',90,'http://sounding.com/blog/?p=260',0,'revision','',0),(147,2,'2008-09-02 15:11:42','2008-09-02 22:11:42','As the summer begins its winddown, I\'ve found that I\'ve been writing some interesting beat-ful music at the same time I\'ve been doing completely abstract sound works. It\'s fun! Each opens the doors in the other, it\'s pretty interesting the way the cross-over happens, and how: even moreso these days, things are sculptural and dimensional.\r\n\r\nFor long periods of time, I feel vaguely disinterested by dance music. It\'s cyclical, and it makes me wonder what my music sounds like. I\'ve never had a singular influence, things always become amalgamations of my experience. I never find myself \"trying to do something like so-and-so\" and rarely ever have a sonic idea in my head prior to composing (it\'s happened, but i\'m really more of an explorer/improvisor when it comes to expressing things musically - i just allow my subconscious to do the driving), but I always do seem to have a good sense for how it all goes together.','haven\'t i always written techno?',0,'','publish','open','open','','havent-i-always-written-techno','','','2008-09-02 15:11:42','2008-09-02 22:11:42','',0,'http://sounding.com/blog/?p=147',0,'post','',0),(148,2,'2008-09-02 15:07:25','2008-09-02 22:07:25','As the summer begins its winddown, I\'ve found that I\'ve been writing some interesting beat-ful music at the same time I\'ve been doing completely abstract sound works. It\'s fun! Each opens the doors in the other, it\'s pretty interesting the way the cross-over happens, and how:','haven\'t i always written techno?',0,'','inherit','open','open','','147-revision','','','2008-09-02 15:07:25','2008-09-02 22:07:25','',147,'http://sounding.com/blog/?p=148',0,'revision','',0),(149,2,'2008-09-02 15:11:30','2008-09-02 22:11:30','As the summer begins its winddown, I\'ve found that I\'ve been writing some interesting beat-ful music at the same time I\'ve been doing completely abstract sound works. It\'s fun! Each opens the doors in the other, it\'s pretty interesting the way the cross-over happens, and how: even moreso these days, things are sculptural and dimensional.\n\nFor long periods of time, I feel vaguely disinterested by dance music. It\'s cyclical, and it makes me wonder what my music sounds like. I\'ve never had a singular influence, things always become amalgamations of my experience. I never find myself \"trying to do something like so-and-so\" and rarely ever have a sonic idea in my head prior to composing (it\'s happened, but i\'m really more of an explorer/improvisor when it comes to expressing things musically), but I always do seem to have a good sense for how it all goes together.','haven\'t i always written techno?',0,'','inherit','open','open','','147-revision-2','','','2008-09-02 15:11:30','2008-09-02 22:11:30','',147,'http://sounding.com/blog/?p=149',0,'revision','',0),(150,2,'2008-09-03 15:17:24','2008-09-03 22:17:24','<a href=\"http://music.ucsd.edu/~tre/\" target=\"_blank\">Tom Erbe</a> is one of the members of the electronic music community whose work I highly respect. Not only is most of his software free, not only are they usable by any skill level, not only are they the most educational electronic music tools i\'ve ever used... I could go on. But the end result is that they sound simple and great.\r\n\r\nAt long last Tom has released the <a href=\"http://www.soundhack.com/\" target=\"_blank\">SoundHack Delay Trio</a>, the description of the algorithms is fantastic, from the announcement:\r\n<blockquote>\"All of these are derived from the same basic delay algorithm: a hermite interpolated delay line with variable modulation, and a feedback loop with dc blocking and saturation. Pitch shifting is achieved with a dual head crossfading delay (ala Eltro Tempophon/Dennis Gabor/Pierre Schaeffer phonogene) and is decidedly low-ﬁ. The saturating feedback also allows them to be great drone and noise generators.\"</blockquote>\r\nAwesome work! Can\'t wait to get this one in action, I have something going now that begs for some new delay. ;)\r\n\r\nTwo of my other favorites of Tom\'s are <strong>decimate+</strong> and of course the ubiquitous <strong>SoundHack</strong>, both available (along with a TON of others) on the <a href=\"http://www.soundhack.com/freeware.php\" target=\"_blank\">SoundHack Freeware page</a>.','SoundHack Delay Trio Released',0,'','publish','open','open','','soundhack-delay-trio-released','','','2008-09-04 09:20:08','2008-09-04 16:20:08','',0,'http://sounding.com/blog/?p=150',0,'post','',0),(151,2,'2008-09-03 15:15:18','2008-09-03 22:15:18','Tom Erbe is one of the members of the electronic music community whose work I highly respect. Not only is most of his software free, not only are the highly usable by any level of knowledge, not only are they the single most educational applied electronic music tools i\'ve ever used... I could go on. But the end result is that they sound simple and great.\n\nAt long last Tom has released the <a href=\"http://www.soundhack.com/\" target=\"_blank\">SoundHack Delay Trio</a>, the description of the algorithms is fantastic, from the announcement:\n<blockquote>\"All of these are derived from the same basic delay algorithm: a hermite interpolated delay line with variable modulation, and a feedback loop with dc blocking and saturation. Pitch shifting is achieved with a dual head crossfading delay (ala Eltro Tempophon/Dennis Gabor/Pierre Schaeffer phonogene) and is decidedly low-ﬁ. The saturating feedback also allows them to be great drone and noise generators.\"</blockquote>\nAwesome work! Can\'t wait to get this one in action.\n\nTwo of my other favorites of Tom\'s are decimate+ and of course','SoundHack Delay Trio Released',0,'','inherit','open','open','','150-revision','','','2008-09-03 15:15:18','2008-09-03 22:15:18','',150,'http://sounding.com/blog/?p=151',0,'revision','',0),(152,2,'2008-09-03 15:17:07','2008-09-03 22:17:07','Tom Erbe is one of the members of the electronic music community whose work I highly respect. Not only is most of his software free, not only are they usable by any skill level, not only are they the most educational electronic music tools i\'ve ever used... I could go on. But the end result is that they sound simple and great.\n\nAt long last Tom has released the <a href=\"http://www.soundhack.com/\" target=\"_blank\">SoundHack Delay Trio</a>, the description of the algorithms is fantastic, from the announcement:\n<blockquote>\"All of these are derived from the same basic delay algorithm: a hermite interpolated delay line with variable modulation, and a feedback loop with dc blocking and saturation. Pitch shifting is achieved with a dual head crossfading delay (ala Eltro Tempophon/Dennis Gabor/Pierre Schaeffer phonogene) and is decidedly low-ﬁ. The saturating feedback also allows them to be great drone and noise generators.\"</blockquote>\nAwesome work! Can\'t wait to get this one in action, I have something going now that begs for some new delay.\n\nTwo of my other favorites of Tom\'s are decimate+ and of course the ubiquitous SoundHack, both available (along with a TON of others) on the <a href=\"http://www.soundhack.com/freeware.php\" target=\"_blank\">SoundHack Freeware page</a>.','SoundHack Delay Trio Released',0,'','inherit','open','open','','150-revision-2','','','2008-09-03 15:17:07','2008-09-03 22:17:07','',150,'http://sounding.com/blog/?p=152',0,'revision','',0),(153,2,'2008-09-03 15:17:24','2008-09-03 22:17:24','Tom Erbe is one of the members of the electronic music community whose work I highly respect. Not only is most of his software free, not only are they usable by any skill level, not only are they the most educational electronic music tools i\'ve ever used... I could go on. But the end result is that they sound simple and great.\r\n\r\nAt long last Tom has released the <a href=\"http://www.soundhack.com/\" target=\"_blank\">SoundHack Delay Trio</a>, the description of the algorithms is fantastic, from the announcement:\r\n<blockquote>\"All of these are derived from the same basic delay algorithm: a hermite interpolated delay line with variable modulation, and a feedback loop with dc blocking and saturation. Pitch shifting is achieved with a dual head crossfading delay (ala Eltro Tempophon/Dennis Gabor/Pierre Schaeffer phonogene) and is decidedly low-ﬁ. The saturating feedback also allows them to be great drone and noise generators.\"</blockquote>\r\nAwesome work! Can\'t wait to get this one in action, I have something going now that begs for some new delay. ;)\r\n\r\nTwo of my other favorites of Tom\'s are <strong>decimate+</strong> and of course the ubiquitous <strong>SoundHack</strong>, both available (along with a TON of others) on the <a href=\"http://www.soundhack.com/freeware.php\" target=\"_blank\">SoundH