ting, but first I\'ll introduce you to what I\'ve been hearing since...\n\nKangding Ray: OR\n\nAndy Stott: Passed Me By / We Stay Together\n\nMarow: + - 0\nThe thing that attracts me to the sound of this album is the brittleness of the loops. Minimal, yes. Sparsely percussive, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. \n\nAril Brikha: Palma EP\n\nSteinbrüchel\n\nOchre - Early Learning\n\nPlakton Wat / Superminerals - c40\n\nPlaid: Scintilli\n\nBiosphere: N-Plants\n\nPhoenecia: Demissions\n\nMartin Schulte: Treasure\n\nAutechre: EPs 1991-2002\n\nAmon Tobin: Isam\n\nDeep Chord: Hash Bar Remnants\n\nAeroc: R+B=?\n\npobrosk\n\nsurgeon\n\nMatthew Mercer: Pianissimo Possibile\n\nLogreybeam: Perhaps\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands\"','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-22','','','2012-01-03 08:12:47','2012-01-03 16:12:47','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/03/492-revision-22/',0,'revision','',0),(516,2,'2012-01-03 13:50:54','2012-01-03 21:50:54','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, but first I\'ll introduce you to what I\'ve been hearing since.\n\nThis may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR\n</em>Raster-Noton\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together\n</em>Modern Love\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nForce-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal, yes. Sparsely percussive, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game there\'s nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc before they changed owners, but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. In case you didn\'t know, this isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc - different owners, different perspective, different attitude.\n\nAril Brikha: Palma EP\n\nSteinbrüchel\n\nOchre - Early Learning\n\nPlakton Wat / Superminerals - c40\n\nPlaid: Scintilli\n\nBiosphere: N-Plants\n\nPhoenecia: Demissions\n\nMartin Schulte: Treasure\n\nAutechre: EPs 1991-2002\n\nAmon Tobin: Isam\nPolarizing doesn\'t even come close to how this album appears through my battered sense of observation. People I know who love it do so for all the right reasons: a lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations. Somewhat like another artist on this list but much more of an eerie disturbing off-kilterness. Guess what: the other side hates it for all the same ones.\n\nDeep Chord: Hash Bar Remnants\n\nAeroc: R+B=?\n\npobrosk\n\nsurgeon\n\nMatthew Mercer: Pianissimo Possibile\n\nLogreybeam: Perhaps\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands\"','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-23','','','2012-01-03 13:50:54','2012-01-03 21:50:54','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/03/492-revision-23/',0,'revision','',0),(518,2,'2