of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR\n</em>Raster-Noton\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together\n</em>Modern Love\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nForce-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal, yes. Sparsely percussive, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game there\'s nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc before they changed owners, but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. In case you didn\'t know, this isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, and unfortunately I don\'t expect the name to ever reach those heights again.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\n<strong>Steinbrüchel</strong>\nsomething??\n\n<strong>Shpongle</strong>\n<em>The God Particle</em>\nTwisted\n\n<strong>Ochre</strong>\n<em>Early Learning</em>\n\n<strong>Skinny Puppy</strong>\n<em>HanDover</em>\nSubconscious\n\n<strong>Plakton Wat / Superminerals</strong>\n<em>c40</em>\n\n<strong>Plaid</strong>\n<em>Scintilli</em>\n\n<strong>Biosphere</strong>\n<em>N-Plants</em>\n\n<strong>Phoenecia</strong>\n<em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Martin Schulte</strong>\nTreasure\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nAmon Tobin: ISAM (Control Over Nature)\nThe word \'polarizing\' doesn\'t even come close... some regular fans really hate it, but the people I know who love it do so for all the right reasons: a lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscope mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the book version, which contains an incredible outlay of artwork by Tessa Farmer, from Amoeba in Hollywood (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz).\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>Pobrosk</strong>\nsomething\n\n<strong>Surgeon</strong>\nblah\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer\n</strong><em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands, i.e. Witch House\"','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-31','','','2012-01-03 20:00:59','2012-01-04 04:00:59','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/03/492-revision-31/',0,'revision','',0),(525,2,'2012-01-03 20:06:43','2012-01-04 04:06:43','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, but first I\'ll introduce you to what I\'ve been hearing since.\n\nThis may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR\n</em>Raster-Noton\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together\n</em>Modern Love\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nForce-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal, yes. Sparsely percussive, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game there\'s nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc before they changed owners, but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. In case you didn\'t know, this isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, and unfortunately I don\'t expect the name to ever reach those heights again.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\n<strong>Steinbrüchel</strong>\nsomething??\n\n<strong>Shpongle</strong>\n<em>The God Particle</em>\nTwisted\n\n<strong>Ochre</strong>\n<em>Early Learning</em>\n\n<strong>Skinny Puppy</strong>\n<em>HanDover</em>\nSubconscious\n\n<strong>Plakton Wat / Superminerals</strong>\n<em>c40</em>\n\n<strong>Plaid</strong>\n<em>Scintilli</em>\n\n<strong>Biosphere</strong>\n<em>N-Plants</em>\n\n<strong>Phoenecia</strong>\n<em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Martin Schulte</strong>\nTreasure\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nAmon Tobin: ISAM (Control Over Nature)\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the right reasons: a lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz).\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>Pobrosk</strong>\nsomething\n\n<strong>Surgeon</strong>\nblah\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer\n</strong><em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands, i.e. Witch House\"','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-32','','','2012-01-03 20:06:43','2012-01-04 04:06:43','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/03/492-revision-32/',0,'revision','',0),(526,2,'2012-01-03 22:01:16','2012-01-04 06:01:16','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, but first I\'ll introduce you to what I\'ve been hearing since.\n\nThis may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nForce-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal, yes. Sparsely percussive, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game there\'s nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc before they changed owners, but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. In case you didn\'t know, this isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, and unfortunately I don\'t expect the name to ever reach those heights again.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\n<strong>Steinbrüchel</strong>\nsomething??\n\n<strong>Shpongle</strong>\n<em>The God Particle</em>\nTwisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears.\n\n<strong>Ochre</strong>\n<em>Early Learning</em>\n\n<strong>Skinny Puppy</strong>\n<em>HanDover</em>\nSubconscious\n\n<strong>Plakton Wat / Superminerals</strong>\n<em>c40</em>\n\n<strong>Plaid</strong>\n<em>Scintilli</em>\n\n<strong>Biosphere</strong>\n<em>N-Plants</em>\n\n<strong>Phoenecia</strong>\n<em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Martin Schulte</strong>\nTreasure\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nAmon Tobin: ISAM (Control Over Nature)\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the right reasons: a lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz).\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n\n\n<strong>Pobrosk</strong>\nsomething\n\n<strong>Surgeon</strong>\nblah\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer\n</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands, i.e. Witch House\"\n\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my new kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever (despite my dislike of most so-called \'hypnagogic pop\'), I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-33','','','2012-01-03 22:01:16','2012-01-04 06:01:16','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/03/492-revision-33/',0,'revision','',0),(528,2,'2012-01-03 23:07:47','2012-01-04 07:07:47','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. In specialized situations, I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. I do that a lot (you should see my collection of Cage books), but sometimes when you\'re commuting you just need a nice solid percussive hook and an electric drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued on strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nForce-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal, yes. Sparsely percussive, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game there\'s nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc before they changed owners, but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\n<strong>Steinbrüchel</strong>\nsomething??\n\n<strong>Shpongle</strong>\n<em>The God Particle</em>\nTwisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. \n\n<strong>Ochre</strong>\n<em>Early Learning</em>\n\n<strong>Skinny Puppy</strong>\n<em>HanDover</em>\nSubconscious\n\n\n\n<strong>Plakton Wat / Superminerals</strong>\n<em>c40</em>\n\n<strong>Biosphere</strong>\n<em>N-Plants</em>\n\n<strong>Phoenecia</strong>\n<em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Martin Schulte</strong>\nTreasure\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nAmon Tobin: ISAM (Control Over Nature)\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the right reasons: a lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz).\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n\n\n<strong>Pobrosk</strong>\nsomething\n\n<strong>Surgeon</strong>\nblah\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer\n</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands, i.e. Witch House\"\n\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my new kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever (despite my dislike of most so-called \'hypnagogic pop\'), I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-35','','','2012-01-03 23:07:47','2012-01-04 07:07:47','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/03/492-revision-35/',0,'revision','',0),(527,2,'2012-01-03 22:23:14','2012-01-04 06:23:14','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. In specialized situations, I can listen to entire albums at a time an genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. I do that a lot (you should see my collection of Cage books), but sometimes when you\'re commuting you just need a nice analog hook and an electric drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<