t time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. In specialized situations, I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. I do that a lot (you should see my collection of Cage books), but sometimes when you\'re commuting you just need a nice solid percussive hook and an electric drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued on strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nForce-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal, yes. Sparsely percussive, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game there\'s nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc before they changed owners, but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\n<strong>Steinbrüchel</strong>\nsomething??\n\n<strong>Shpongle</strong>\n<em>The God Particle</em>\nTwisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. Some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, so it\'s nice these are somewhat oldskool. I especially like the Pink Floyd mimicking, a lot like how Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\" does. I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of sounds like these.\n\n<strong>Ochre</strong>\n<em>Early Learning</em>\n\n<strong>Skinny Puppy</strong>\n<em>HanDover</em>\nSubconscious\n\n\n\n<strong>Plakton Wat / Superminerals</strong>\n<em>c40</em>\n\n<strong>Biosphere</strong>\n<em>N-Plants</em>\n\n<strong>Phoenecia</strong>\n<em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Martin Schulte</strong>\nTreasure\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nAmon Tobin: ISAM (Control Over Nature)\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the right reasons: a lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz).\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n\n\n<strong>Pobrosk</strong>\nsomething\n\n<strong>Surgeon</strong>\nblah\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer\n</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands, i.e. Witch House\"\n\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my new kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever (despite my dislike of most so-called \'hypnagogic pop\'), I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-36','','','2012-01-03 23:14:20','2012-01-04 07:14:20','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/03/492-revision-36/',0,'revision','',0),(530,2,'2012-01-04 07:52:24','2012-01-04 15:52:24','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. In specialized situations, I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. I do that a lot (you should see my collection of Cage books), but sometimes when you\'re commuting you just need a nice solid percussive hook and an electric drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued on strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nForce-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal, yes. Sparsely percussive, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game there\'s nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc before they changed owners, but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\n<strong>Steinbrüchel</strong>\nsomething??\n\n<strong>Shpongle</strong>\n<em>The God Particle</em>\nTwisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. Some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, so it\'s nice these are somewhat oldskool. I especially like the Pink Floyd mimicking, a lot like how Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\" does. I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of sounds like these.\n\n<strong>Ochre</strong>\n<em>Early Learning</em>\n\n<strong>Skinny Puppy</strong>\n<em>HanDover</em>\nSubconscious\n\n\n\n<strong>Plakton Wat / Superminerals</strong>\n<em>c40</em>\n\n<strong>Biosphere</strong>\n<em>N-Plants</em>\n\n<strong>Phoenecia</strong>\n<em>Demissions</em>\n\n\n\n<strong>Martin Schulte</strong>\nTreasure\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nAmon Tobin: ISAM (Control Over Nature)\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n\n\n<strong>Pobrosk</strong>\nsomething\n\n<strong>Surgeon</strong>\nblah\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer\n</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands, i.e. Witch House\"\n\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-37','','','2012-01-04 07:52:24','2012-01-04 15:52:24','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/04/492-revision-37/',0,'revision','',0),(531,2,'2012-01-04 08:09:50','2012-01-04 16:09:50','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. In specialized situations, I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot, but sometimes when you\'re commuting you just need a nice solid percussive hook and a crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued on strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special style of dimly lit underground basement club 30\" speakers in your ears deep house. And that\'s what this EP provides. Just a taste of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of driving dark rhythm, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought melodic display and just the right amount of builds, expertly structured, without pretense (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there).\n\n<strong>Steinbrüchel</strong>\nsomething??\n\n<strong>Shpongle</strong>\n<em>The God Particle</em>\nTwisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. Some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, so it\'s nice these are somewhat oldskool. I especially like the Pink Floyd mimicking, a lot like how Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\" does. I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of sounds like these.\n\n<strong>Ochre</strong>\n<em>Early Learning</em>\n\n<strong>Skinny Puppy</strong>\n<em>HanDover</em>\nSubconscious\n\n\n\n<strong>Plakton Wat / Superminerals</strong>\n<em>c40</em>\n\n<strong>Biosphere</strong>\n<em>N-Plants</em>\n\n<strong>Phoenecia</strong>\n<em>Demissions</em>\n\n\n\n<strong>Martin Schulte</strong>\nTreasure\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nAmon Tobin: ISAM (Control Over Nature)\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n\n\n<strong>Pobrosk</strong>\nsomething\n\n<strong>Surgeon</strong>\nblah\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer\n</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands, i.e. Witch House\"\n\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-38','','','2012-01-04 08:09:50','2012-01-04 16:09:50','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/04/492-revision-38/',0,'revision','',0),(535,2,'2012-01-05 14:40:54','2012-01-05 22:40:54','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. In specialized situations, I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot, but sometimes when you\'re commuting you just need a nice solid percussive hook and a crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued on strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Ochre</strong>\n<em>Early Learning</em>\n\n<strong>Biosphere</strong>\n\n<em>N-Plants</em>\n\n<strong>Phoenecia</strong>\n<em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Martin Schulte</strong>\nTreasure\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I &amp; II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>Pobrosk</strong>\nsomething\n\n<strong>Surgeon</strong>\nblah\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands, i.e. Witch House\"\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-42','','','2012-01-05 14:40:54','2012-01-05 22:40:54','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/05/492-revision-42/',0,'revision','',0),(532,2,'2012-01-05 11:27:29','2012-01-05 19:27:29','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. In specialized situations, I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot, but sometimes when you\'re commuting you just need a nice solid percussive hook and a crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued on strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Steinbrüchel</strong>\nsomething??\n\n<strong>Shpongle</strong>\n<em>The God Particle</em>\nTwisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Ochre</strong>\n<em>Early Learning</em>\n\nOneohtrix Point Never\nReplica\nS\n\n<strong>Plankton Wat / Superminerals\n</strong><em>c40</em>\n\n<strong>Biosphere</strong>\n<em>N-Plants</em>\n\n<strong>Phoenecia</strong>\n<em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Martin Schulte</strong>\nTreasure\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nAmon Tobin: ISAM (Control Over Nature)\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I &amp; II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>Pobrosk</strong>\nsomething\n\n<strong>Surgeon</strong>\nblah\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer\n</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\n\"weird titled atmospheric bands, i.e. Witch House\"\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-39','','','2012-01-05 11:27:29','2012-01-05 19:27:29','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/05/492-revision-39/',0,'revision','',0),(533,2,'2012-01-05 11:29:00','2012-01-05 19:29:00','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me 