th paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension,  \n\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\n\n \n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-52','','','2012-01-05 20:00:23','2012-01-06 04:00:23','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/05/492-revision-52/',0,'revision','',0),(547,2,'2012-01-05 22:01:09','2012-01-06 06:01:09','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nI have every single one of these EPs on vinyl, and a lot of them digitally, so when this came out I was ecstatic.\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n \n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n \n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. I\'m sure I\'m not in the minority when I pronounce emphatically that I place this even above IDM as the worst-title-that-stuck on the planet. You\'ll be hard pressed to find the heritage with house music in a lot of this, so I\'ll keep to what it actually sounds like, which is more of a dark industrial electro dub... now see, DIED Music is much better. In fact, to be strictly true to the tenets of the genre, let\'s go with DłΣÐ Music...\n\nThis is a fairly new phenomenon, influenced by paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension... there aren\'t just a few styles commingling here, it\'s like a step beyond style, where so many intersecting idioms combine to create a newness that emerges from simply being together.\n\nThese three are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has touched me more than any other.\n\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-54','','','2012-01-05 22:01:09','2012-01-06 06:01:09','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/05/492-revision-54/',0,'revision','',0),(546,2,'2012-01-05 21:57:09','2012-01-06 05:57:09','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nI have every single one of these EPs on vinyl, and a lot of them digitally, so when this came out I was ecstatic.\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n \n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n \n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. I\'m sure I\'m not in the minority when I pronounce emphatically that I place this even above IDM as the worst-title-that-stuck on the planet. You\'ll be hard pressed to find the heritage with house music in a lot of this, so I\'ll keep to what it actually sounds like, which is more of a dark industrial electro dub... now see, DIED Music is much better. In fact, to be strictly true to the tenets of the genre, let\'s go with DłΣÐ Music...\n\nThis is a fairly new phenomenon, influenced by paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension... there aren\'t just a few styles commingling here, it\'s like a step beyond style, where so many intersecting idioms create a newness simply from being combined together.\n\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\n\n \n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-53','','','2012-01-05 21:57:09','2012-01-06 05:57:09','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/05/492-revision-53/',0,'revision','',0),(549,2,'2012-01-06 15:45:16','2012-01-06 23:45:16','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>The Black Dog\n</strong><em>Liber </em>\nDust Science\n\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up within the past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!) complete with a remix collection. The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient Music for Real Airports, but they are definitively more techno, and perfect for the dancefloor.\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I &amp; II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. I\'m sure I\'m not in the minority when I pronounce emphatically that I place this even above IDM as the worst-title-that-stuck on the planet. You\'ll be hard pressed to find the heritage with house music in a lot of this, so I\'ll keep to what it actually sounds like, which is more of a dark industrial electro dub... now see, DIED Music is much better. In fact, to be strictly true to the tenets of the genre, let\'s go with DłΣÐ Music...\n\nThis is a fairly new phenomenon in electronica, influenced with paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension,\n\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-56','','','2012-01-06 15:45:16','2012-01-06 23:45:16','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/06/492-revision-56/',0,'revision','',0),(548,2,'2012-01-05 22:21:46','2012-01-06 06:21:46','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you need a well placed melodic or rhythmic hook along a crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\nTwo words: desert party.\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>Autechre</strong>\n<em>EPs 1991-2002</em>\nWarp\n\nI have every single one of these EPs on vinyl, so when this came out I was ecstatic.\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I immediately buy it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is a huge exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\nI\'m sure I don\'t have to mention the dearth of piano-based electro-acoustic works out there. It\'s almost oppressive, and a great majority stick to the lighter side of things for unknown reasons probably related to sentimentality or even a lack of imagination when it comes to combining electronica with such an elder instrument. Here, it becomes a sound source that isn\'t any more important than the structures and rhythms that combine them together.\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. I\'m sure I\'m not in the minority when I pronounce emphatically that I place this even above \'IDM\' as the worst-title-that-stuck on the planet. You\'ll be hard pressed to find the heritage with house music in a lot of this, so I\'d keep to what it actually sounds like: more of a Dark Industrial Electro Dub... now see, there you go. DIED Music is much better. In fact, to be strictly true to the tenets of the genre, let\'s go with DłΣÐ Music...\n\nThis is a fairly new phenomenon, influenced by many paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension... there aren\'t just a few styles commingling here, it\'s like a step beyond style, where so many intersecting idioms combine that a newness emerges from simply being together.\n\nThese three are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like these - the compilations especially - not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what rises a bit above the others (in my own musical opinion anyway).\n\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-55','','','2012-01-05 22:21:46','2012-01-06 06:21:46','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/05/492-revision-55/',0,'revision','',0),(550,2,'2012-01-06 15:46:40','2012-01-06 23:46:40','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>The Black Dog\n</strong><em>Liber </em>\nDust Science\n\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up within the past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!) complete with a remix collection. The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient Music for Real Airports, but they are definitively more straight-ahead techno (with a tBd twist, of course), and perfect for the dancefloor.\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I &amp; II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. I\'m sure I\'m not in the minority when I pronounce emphatically that I place this even above IDM as the worst-title-that-stuck on the planet. You\'ll be hard pressed to find the heritage with house music in a lot of this, so I\'ll keep to what it actually sounds like, which is more of a dark industrial electro dub... now see, DIED Music is much better. In fact, to be strictly true to the tenets of the genre, let\'s go with DłΣÐ Music...\n\nThis is a fairly new phenomenon in electronica, influenced with paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension,\n\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-57','','','2012-01-06 15:46:40','2012-01-06 23:46:40','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/06/492-revision-57/',0,'revision','',0),(552,2,'2012-01-06 17:18:51','2012-01-07 01:18:51','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>The Black Dog\n</strong><em>Liber </em>\nDust Science\n\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up these past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!), complete with a remix collection. The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient <em>Music for Real Airports</em>, but they are definitively more straight-ahead techno (with a tBd twist, of course), perfect for the dancefloor.\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nBandcamp\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. I\'m sure I\'m not in the minority when I pronounce emphatically that I place this even above IDM as the worst-title-that-stuck on the planet. You\'ll be hard pressed to find the heritage with house music in a lot of this, so I\'ll keep to what it actually sounds like, which is more of a dark industrial electro dub... now see, DIED Music is much better. In fact, to be strictly true to the tenets of the genre, let\'s go with DłΣÐ Music...\n\nThis is a fairly new phenomenon in electronica, influenced with paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension,\n\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-59','','','2012-01-06 17:18:51','2012-01-07 01:18:51','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/06/492-revision-59/',0,'revision','',0),(551,2,'2012-01-06 15:56:30','2012-01-06 23:56:30','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and this may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\r\n\r\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\r\n\r\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\r\n<em>OR</em>\r\nRaster-Noton\r\n\r\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\r\n\r\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\r\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\r\nModern Love\r\n\r\nI am so happy the thick pulsing washing machine textured off-balance beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so.\r\n\r\n<strong>Marow</strong>\r\n<em>+ - 0</em>\r\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\r\n\r\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\r\n\r\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\r\n<em>Palma EP</em>\r\n\r\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\r\n\r\n<strong>Shpongle\r\n</strong><em>The God Particle\r\n</em>Twisted\r\n\r\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\r\n\r\n<strong>Phoenecia\r\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\r\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\r\nPerlon\r\n\r\n<strong>The Black Dog\r\n</strong><em>Liber </em>\r\nDust Science\r\n\r\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up within the past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!) complete with a remix collection. The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient Music for Real Airports, but they are definitively more straight-ahead techno (with a tBd twist, of course), and perfect for the dancefloor.\r\n\r\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\r\nNinja Tune\r\n\r\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\r\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I &amp; II</em>\r\nEchospace\r\n\r\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\r\n\r\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\r\n<em>R+B=?</em>\r\nGhostly\r\n\r\n<strong>John Tejada\r\n</strong><em>Parabolas\r\n</em>Kompakt\r\n\r\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\r\n\r\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\r\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\r\nBandcamp\r\n\r\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\r\n<em>Perhaps</em>\r\n\r\nShoegaze klezmer.\r\n\r\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\r\n~▲††▲~\r\nPhantasma Disques\r\n\r\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\r\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\r\nTundra Dub\r\n\r\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. I\'m sure I\'m not in the minority when I pronounce emphatically that I place this even above IDM as the worst-title-that-stuck on the planet. You\'ll be hard pressed to find the heritage with house music in a lot of this, so I\'ll keep to what it actually sounds like, which is more of a dark industrial electro dub... now see, DIED Music is much better. In fact, to be strictly true to the tenets of the genre, let\'s go with DłΣÐ Music...\r\n\r\nThis is a fairly new phenomenon in electronica, influenced with paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension,\r\n\r\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\r\n\r\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\r\n\r\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-58','','','2012-01-06 15:56:30','2012-01-06 23:56:30','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/06/492-revision-58/',0,'revision','',0),(553,2,'2012-01-08 12:46:40','2012-01-08 20:46:40','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and the following may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the throbbing washing machine multi-textured off-balance-beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so, drawing the ear into a swaying communion.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>The Black Dog\n</strong><em>Liber 4</em>\nDust Science\n\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up these past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!), complete with a remix collection. The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient <em>Music for Real Airports</em>, but they are definitively more straight-ahead techno (with a tBd twist, of course), perfect for the dancefloor.\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I &amp; II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nself-released\n\nIf you listen to any amount of electro-acoustic music you\'re as painfully aware as I of the the wealth of piano works. idioms... broken... glitched... expectations frustrated, equal footing with the structure and form instead of attempting some kind of accompaniment...\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. I\'m sure I\'m not in the minority when I pronounce emphatically that I place this even above IDM as the worst-title-that-stuck on the planet. You\'ll be hard pressed to find the heritage with house music in a lot of this, so I\'ll keep to what it actually sounds like, which is more of a dark industrial electro dub... now see, DIED Music is much better. In fact, to be strictly true to the tenets of the genre, let\'s go with DłΣÐ Music...\n\nThis is a fairly new phenomenon in electronica, influenced with paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension,\n\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-60','','','2012-01-08 12:46:40','2012-01-08 20:46:40','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/08/492-revision-60/',0,'revision','',0),(554,2,'2012-01-08 12:50:36','2012-01-08 20:50:36','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and the following may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the throbbing washing machine multi-textured off-balance-beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so, drawing the ear into a swaying communion.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>The Black Dog\n</strong><em>Liber [ Kult / Temple / Nox / Chaos ]</em>\nDust Science\n\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up these past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!), complete with a remix collection. The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient <em>Music for Real Airports</em>, but they are definitively more straight-ahead techno (with a tBd twist, of course), perfect for the dancefloor.\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I &amp; II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nself-released\n\nIf you listen to any amount of electro-acoustic music you\'re as painfully aware as I of the the wealth of piano works. idioms... broken... glitched... expectations frustrated, equal footing with the structure and form instead of attempting some kind of accompaniment...\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House.This is a fairly new phenomenon in electronica, influenced with paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension,\n\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-61','','','2012-01-08 12:50:36','2012-01-08 20:50:36','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/08/492-revision-61/',0,'revision','',0),(555,2,'2012-01-08 12:52:44','2012-01-08 20:52:44','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and the following may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the throbbing washing machine multi-textured off-balance-beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so, drawing the ear into a swaying communion.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>The Black Dog\n</strong><em>Liber [ Kult / Temple / Nox / Chaos ]</em>\nDust Science\n\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up these past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!), complete with a remix collection. The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient <em>Music for Real Airports</em>, but they are definitively more straight-ahead techno (with a tBd twist, of course), perfect for the dancefloor.\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I &amp; II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nself-released\n\nIf you listen to any amount of electro-acoustic music you\'re as painfully aware as I of the the wealth of piano works. idioms... broken... glitched... expectations frustrated, equal footing with the structure and form instead of attempting some kind of accompaniment...\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. This is a fairly new phenomenon in electronica, influenced with paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension,\n\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-62','','','2012-01-08 12:52:44','2012-01-08 20:52:44','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/08/492-revision-62/',0,'revision','',0),(556,2,'2012-01-08 12:54:28','2012-01-08 20:54:28','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and the following may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\r\n\r\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\r\n\r\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\r\n<em>OR</em>\r\nRaster-Noton\r\n\r\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\r\n\r\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\r\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\r\nModern Love\r\n\r\nI am so happy the throbbing washing machine multi-textured off-balance-beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so, drawing the ear into a swaying communion.\r\n\r\n<strong>Marow</strong>\r\n<em>+ - 0</em>\r\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\r\n\r\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\r\n\r\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\r\n<em>Palma EP</em>\r\n\r\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\r\n\r\n<strong>Shpongle\r\n</strong><em>The God Particle\r\n</em>Twisted\r\n\r\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\r\n\r\n<strong>Phoenecia\r\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\r\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\r\nPerlon\r\n\r\n<strong>The Black Dog\r\n</strong><em>Liber [ Kult / Temple / Nox / Chaos ]</em>\r\nDust Science\r\n\r\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up these past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!), complete with a remix collection. The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient <em>Music for Real Airports</em>, but they are definitively more straight-ahead techno (with a tBd twist, of course), perfect for the dancefloor.\r\n\r\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\r\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\r\nNinja Tune\r\n\r\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\r\n\r\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\r\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I &amp; II</em>\r\nEchospace\r\n\r\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\r\n\r\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\r\n<em>R+B=?</em>\r\nGhostly\r\n\r\n<strong>John Tejada\r\n</strong><em>Parabolas\r\n</em>Kompakt\r\n\r\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\r\n\r\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\r\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\r\nself-released\r\n\r\nIf you listen to any amount of electro-acoustic music you\'re as painfully aware as I of the the wealth of piano works. idioms... broken... glitched... expectations frustrated, equal footing with the structure and form instead of attempting some kind of accompaniment...\r\n\r\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\r\n<em>Perhaps</em>\r\n\r\nShoegaze klezmer.\r\n\r\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\r\n~▲††▲~\r\nPhantasma Disques\r\n\r\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\r\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\r\nTundra Dub\r\n\r\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. It might be endearing\r\n\r\nThis is a fairly new phenomenon in electronica, influenced with paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension,\r\n\r\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\r\n\r\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\r\n\r\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-63','','','2012-01-08 12:54:28','2012-01-08 20:54:28','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/08/492-revision-63/',0,'revision','',0),(557,2,'2012-01-10 07:49:49','2012-01-10 15:49:49','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and the following may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the throbbing washing machine multi-textured off-balance-beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so, drawing the ear into a swaying communion.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>The Black Dog\n</strong><em>Liber Dogma / [ Kult / Temple / Nox ]</em>\nDust Science\n\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up these past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!). The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient <em>Music for Real Airports</em>, but they are definitively more straight-ahead techno. Dogma, on the other hand, is close to one of my favorite listens of the year, released to be a snapshot of what tBd does live, and the result is a beautifully organic evolving mass of electronic exploration and funky groovability. \n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nself-released\n\nIf you listen to any amount of electro-acoustic music you\'re as painfully aware as I of the the wealth of piano works. idioms... broken... glitched... expectations frustrated, equal footing with the structure and form instead of attempting some kind of accompaniment...\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House. It might be endearing\n\nThis is a fairly new phenomenon in electronica, influenced with paths blazed by bands like Coil and Skinny Puppy, but emerging into another dimension,\n\nThese three releases are actually one single artist and two remix albums, because I really feel like those compilations especially not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-64','','','2012-01-10 07:49:49','2012-01-10 15:49:49','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/10/492-revision-64/',0,'revision','',0),(558,2,'2012-01-10 08:06:13','2012-01-10 16:06:13','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and the following may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the throbbing washing machine multi-textured off-balance-beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so, drawing the ear into a swaying communion.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>The Black Dog\n</strong><em>Liber Dogma / [ Kult / Temple / Nox ]</em>\nDust Science\n\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up these past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!). The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient <em>Music for Real Airports</em>, but they are definitively more straight-ahead techno. Dogma, on the other hand, is close to one of my favorite listens of the year, released to be a snapshot of what tBd does live, and the result is a beautifully organic evolving mass of electronic exploration and funky groovability. \n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I & II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nself-released\n\nIf you listen to any amount of electro-acoustic music you\'re as painfully aware as I of the the wealth of piano works. idioms... broken... glitched... expectations frustrated, equal footing with the structure and form instead of attempting some kind of accompaniment...\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House (and I know you\'re thinking, \"RUN\'s house!\"). The alternatives are maybe not that better... \'Okkvlt\' is probably what works best for me, but there\'s also \'Zombie Rave\' or the more musicological but equally confusing term \'drag\'... not so easy to tell what they actually describe. To that end, I feel like these releases not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range of styles, a rave element dialed down to icey glacial projections, plenty of noise and drone elements scattered throughout. Beyond style really, where a lot of genres meet up just to melt together in an underworld of sublimity.\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-65','','','2012-01-10 08:06:13','2012-01-10 16:06:13','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/10/492-revision-65/',0,'revision','',0),(559,2,'2012-01-10 09:43:13','2012-01-10 17:43:13','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and the following may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\n\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\n\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\n<em>OR</em>\nRaster-Noton\n\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, all extremely nice static buzz filled phat bass ear candy with more of an organic character than your typical release from here.\n\n<strong>Andy Stott</strong>\n<em>Passed Me By / We Stay Together</em>\nModern Love\n\nI am so happy the throbbing washing machine multi-textured off-balance-beat dub techno sound has continued strong thanks to this artist. The constantly appearing layers are the most surprising and pleasing parts of these tracks, looping sound combinations you just don\'t expect, spanning a wide spectrum. There emerge strange hypnotizing rhythms, thankfully not always percussively so, drawing the ear into a swaying communion.\n\n<strong>Marow</strong>\n<em>+ - 0</em>\nMille-Plateaux / Force-X-Inc.\n\nMinimal sound, yes. Sparsely peppered beats, check. Thinly harmonized pointillistic impressions of melody, present and called for. You could even say somewhat, well, derivative. But to be honest, at this point in the electronica game, there is nothing better than someone who comes along and hits a style out of the park. The label, however, seems to be having an identity crisis. The demo for this CD (which I happened upon at work, left alone on the kitchen table) has it on the \"Mille-Plateaux\" label, which used to be the more abstract side of ForceInc (before changing owners), but they seem to have \'moved\' the release to \"Force-X-Inc\", which used to be the <em>harder techno</em> side of the label, that is now - especially considering this record - confusingly not that at all. This isn\'t your father\'s ForceInc, unfortunately.\n\n<strong>Aril Brikha</strong>\n<em>Palma EP</em>\n\nGetting involved in the Chicago house DJ scene made me a huge fawning sucker for that special deep style of dimly lit underground basement club speakers-in-your-ears house. This EP provides a glimmer of that sound, a small sliver of a view into a circling mass of that driving dance beat, but with the added flavor of a nicely wrought darker melodic display (and frankly this guy can be super cheeseball, so kudos there) and just the right amount of unpretentious builds, expertly structured above thick analog basslines.\n\n<strong>Shpongle\n</strong><em>The God Particle\n</em>Twisted\n\nI can\'t deny my love of this band and when even a small two-track release appears I\'m all ears. So although some of their tracks get way too poppy for my taste, it\'s perfect that these are somewhat oldskool, and I especially love the Pink Floyd mimickery (not entirely unlike Download\'s \"Flight of the Luminous Insects\"). I guess there\'s a lot I like in tracks like these that remind me of my favorite times as a kid listening to the unfolding of albums like Dark Side of the Moon, and that can\'t be a bad thing.\n\n<strong>Phoenecia\n</strong><em>Demissions</em>\n\n<strong>Margaret Dygas</strong>\n<em>Margaret Dygas</em>\nPerlon\n\n<strong>The Black Dog\n</strong><em>Liber Dogma / [ Kult / Temple / Nox ]</em>\nDust Science\n\nIt was a great day when Ken Downie teamed up with Dust Science to resurrect The Black Dog in all its weird glory. It\'s like a hole was in electronica and nobody ever knew it until new albums and remixes started showing up these past few years, and now here\'s a slew of new tracks (colored vinyl if you\'re one of the lucky ones!). The label page says these are meant a continuation of the more darkly ambient <em>Music for Real Airports</em>, but they are definitively more straight-ahead techno. Dogma, on the other hand, is close to one of my favorite listens of the year, released to be a snapshot of what tBd does live, and the result is a beautifully organic evolving mass of electronic exploration and funky groovability.\n\n<strong>Amon Tobin</strong>\n<em>ISAM (Control Over Nature)</em>\nNinja Tune\n\nSome regular fans were real disappointed, but the people I know who love it probably do so for all the same reasons i do: a poignant lack of sampling other works, intense abstract sound design, at times tableau-like, to-the-point sonic explorations, familiar filtered analog synth kaleidoscopes mixed with ample digital acrobatics and just the right touch of an eerily disturbing off-kilterness. I got the fantastic blue-fabric bound book version from Amoeba in LA, which is this amazing outlay of a miniature insect-like world created by Tessa Farmer (interestingly enough the very day I interviewed at Buzz). I share some heritage with the album too, mastered as it is by my friend Shawn (aka Twerk) over at AudibleOddities.\n\n<strong>Deep Chord</strong>\n<em>Hash Bar Remnants, Pts. I &amp; II</em>\nEchospace\n\nRod Modell has got the knack for delivering a constant stream of floaty reverberating dub, and these installments are no exception. Slightly ambient tracks with lighter drums sit neatly beside heavier beats that could easily be mixed into techno - in fact all two volumes provide a wealth of nice and long dub house tracks for the discerning mixologist (there is even a follow-up release of loops from these records).\n\n<strong>Aeroc</strong>\n<em>R+B=?</em>\nGhostly\n\n<strong>John Tejada\n</strong><em>Parabolas\n</em>Kompakt\n\nUsually when I see any remix on something done by Tejada, I get it, but have never been so much into the full albums. This one is the exception, a stellar atmospheric and minimal techno release, not to mention I just love having a Tejada vinyl with the ubiquitous Kompakt circles.\n\n<strong>Matthew Mercer</strong>\n<em>Pianissimo Possibile</em>\nself-released\n\nIf you listen to any amount of electro-acoustic music you\'re as painfully aware as I of the the glut of piano works. Fortunately idioms those... here broken... glitched... expectations frustrated, equal footing with the structure and form instead of attempting some kind of accompaniment... driven and poignant expositions. These tracks always make me check the iPod for what artist it is.\n\n<strong>Logreybeam</strong>\n<em>Perhaps</em>\n\nShoegaze klezmer.\n\n<strong>~▲†▲~</strong>\n~▲††▲~\nPhantasma Disques\n\n<strong>∆AIMON</strong>\n<em>AMEN / AMEN Remixes</em>\nTundra Dub\n\nWhen you\'re actually searching through the underground for new things instead of just allowing them to pop up, you tend to run into some pretty awesomely strange shit (I mentioned the strange shit, right?). So first of all, I hate this genre title: Witch House (and I know you\'re thinking, \"RUN\'s house!\"). The alternatives are maybe not that better... \'Okkvlt\' is probably what works best for me, but there\'s also \'Zombie Rave\' or the more musicological but equally confusing term \'drag\'... not so easy to tell what they actually describe. To that end, I feel like these releases not only encapsulate a lot of what I\'ve heard from this style, but also what has gotten through to me more than other stuff. Orchestral, subtle folk, wide range of analog synth timbres, a rave element dialed down to icey glacial projections, plenty of noise and drone elements scattered throughout. Beyond style really, where a lot of genres meet up to melt together in an underworld of aural sublimity.\n\nHow Did I Find These Sounds?\n\nYou\'re probably wondering, how in the fuck does this guy find such completely off the wall and yet totally awesome music? For one, I read The Wire, but I have to admit I haven\'t been reading my subscription for almost a year, being severely hooked on downloading and reading fiction on my kindle while commuting. To supplement my lack of attention to possibly the greatest music mag ever, I pay attention to some blogs and IRC channels that keep me just as updated on the mysteries of the universe. Without fanfare, here\'s a few I can recommend:','Listening in 2011',0,'','inherit','open','open','','492-revision-66','','','2012-01-10 09:43:13','2012-01-10 17:43:13','',492,'http://sounding.com/blog/2012/01/10/492-revision-66/',0,'revision','',0),(560,2,'2012-01-10 09:43:59','2012-01-10 17:43:59','Three years ago was the last time I did any kind of \"year\'s review\" of aural nourishment, and I sort of feel the need to do it again. <a title=\"My best 24 hours of music in 2008\" href=\"https://sounding.com/blog/2009/01/05/my-best-24-hours-of-music-in-2008/\">Those 24 hours of music</a> are worth revisiting, and the following may not even count as a \"best of,\" but it is some of the best music I\'ve heard this year, and I listen to an awful lot. Maybe call it a \"compendium\"? No that sounds too boring. In actuality this list is simply nothing more than a bunch of shit that goes on my iPod and ends up staying there for longer than it takes for me to get bored of it.\r\n\r\nAnd yeah, there\'s some strange shit indeed.\r\n\r\n<strong>Kangding Ray</strong>\r\n<em>OR</em>\r\nRaster-Noton\r\n\r\nI like this label, I really do. I can listen to entire albums at a time and genuinely enjoy it on a purely sonic level. And I do that a lot! It\'s just that, sometimes when you\'re commuting, you just need a well placed melodic hook alongside the crunchy drone to propel those glitchy electric spark beats along. Check out older albums too, 