infrastructure reliability need in-house. Do the research and compare, make the investment that makes the most sense for your team. Don\'t be fooled, though. Either way, you\'re buying it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','To Build or To Buy, that is the Contradiction.',0,'','inherit','closed','closed','','1006-revision-v1','','','2019-02-08 16:46:51','2019-02-09 00:46:51','',1006,'https://sounding.com/blog/2019/02/08/1006-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1021,2,'2019-02-08 16:47:47','2019-02-09 00:47:47','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It\'s dead simple. Focus on your team and product.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":1011,\"align\":\"right\",\"width\":373,\"height\":371} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"alignright is-resized\"><img src=\"https://sounding.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/breadboard.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1011\" width=\"373\" height=\"371\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yes! An easy tweetable answer! Except that it\'s loaded with questions and assumptions. Instead, what I will talk about here are <em>technology decisions</em>. Those that really matter are about things that elevate your ability to build what you are building at the velocity you need.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In operations and SRE, we are not only tasked with evaluating and testing technologies, we are often requested (or sometimes instructed) to support the decisions others make. This isn\'t an ideal situation, and in some cases, impractical because it feels like a policing. In fact, it might sound a little selfish to think that SRE needs the ability to say \"yay\" or \"nay\" to a decision. If you think that feels slightly siloed, you\'d be right. I prefer working with all vested parties to come up with a solution that fits the problem, not just make blind leaps of faith on a particular platform. Flexibility and cooperative evaluation work really really well, believe it or no